Explanation of the new urban schemes
--------------------------------------

* URBAN-1T (Default option)
The original JULES urban scheme with one urban tile. The properties of the
urban tile are not currently set through the UMUI. If you wish to change
these a hand edit is required to alter &JULES_NVEGPARM. Possibly other
namelists that might want to be altered would include &JULES_Z0H_Z0M and
&JULES_ELEVATE.

Selecting this option sets all the switches in &URBAN_SWITCHES to .FALSE.
ensuring that the new urban schemes are not in use.


* URBAN-2T
Essentially the same as the original one tile urban scheme (URBAN-1T), but
instead of one urban tile there are now two; urban_canyon & urban_roof. The
urban_canyon and urban_roof land fractions are calculated using the urban
geometry variable wrr or "w/r ratio", where:
w = width of the canyon
r = width of the canyon + roof

For 2D canyon geometry this is equivalent to the fraction of the urban tile
that is canyon.

There is no extra physics for this scheme just different parameters, which are
set via the table. The parameters are not spatially variant. The suggested
parameters are the same as the nvegparm urban parameters with a lower roof heat
capacity. These parameters have still to be evaluated so are likely to change
in the future.

There are a number of switches, which belong to &URBAN_SWITCHES, that are set
by using this option:
l_urban2t   = T
l_moruses_* = F


* MORUSES
Builds on URBAN-2T and has four new physical processes parametrised. MORUSES
has the advantage that parameters are derived from values measurable from urban
fabric and geometry, allowing it to more accurately represent the urban
surface. The new parameterisations are briefly described as follows:

1. Shortwave radiative exchange in the form of an effective canyon albedo
   (l_moruses_albedo)

   Includes shading and multiple reflections, which depends on building
   materials, geometry and zenith angle.

2. Long-wave radiative exchange in the form of an effective canyon emissivity
   (l_moruses_emissivity)

   !!!NB: This has been DISABLED until the radiation scheme has caught up with
      variable tile emissivity!!!

   Includes multiple reflections, which depends on building materials and
   geometry.

3. Transfer of heat in the form of effective roughness length for heat and
   momentum (l_moruses_rough)

   * Effective roughness lengths for momentum and displacement heights can
     either be provided as an ancillary, if the empirical relationships are not
     used (see below), or can be calculated using the MacDonald et al. (1998)
     formulation, which makes use of urban geometry (l_moruses_macdonald).

   * Effective roughness length for heat has a physical basis and is not
     calculated as a fraction of momentum. It depends on the geometry of the
     canyon, which affects the recirculation of the jet within the canyon. Flow
     within the canyon can be broken down into two regions; the recirculation
     and ventilation regions, where the recirculation region forms in the wake
     of each building. Three different flow regimes are represented:

     1. Isolated roughness - Canyon has separate recirculation and a
        ventilation regions

     2. Wake interference - Recirculation region begins to impinge on the
        downstream building

     3. Skimming flow - Recirculation region fills the entire canyon

     The effective roughness length for heat is calculated using a resistance
     network within these regions.

4. Thermal inertia and coupling with underlying soil (l_moruses_storage)

   The road only is conductively coupled to the underlying soil, whereas the
   walls and roof are uncoupled and have a zero-flux boundary condition. As
   MORUSES only has two tiles, this is parametrised using a canyon scaling
   factor. The roof has a lower thermal inertia and can respond more rapidly to
   changes in forcing. The heat capacities of the canyon and roof are
   calculated using the properties of the urban fabric and the geometry of the
   canyon.

Urban parameters that are not parameterised by MORUSES can either be specified
by the user or defaults, which are the same as the default URBAN-2T values, can
be used. The user specified values are set via the table and entry boxes below
the table.

A number of switches can be set to enable MORUSES. Each of the four
parameterisations above are associated with an individual switch to allow them
to be selected individually. If the four main parameter switches are disabled
the user has essentially chosen to run URBAN-2T and it is suggested that this
option should be chosen instead.

The default switches are:
l_urban2t   = T
l_moruses_* = T, except for emissivity, which for the time being is disabled

When any switch is not used the model needs to be provided with suitable
alternatives in the entry boxes provided as follows:

Switch                    Set                         Variable names
l_moruses_albedo     = F  Snow covered albedo         albsnc_c   albsnc_rf
                          Snow-free albedo            albsnf_c
l_moruses_emissivity = F  Emissivity                  emis_c
l_moruses_rough      = F  Roughness length            z0_c       z0_rf
                          Ratio of roughness lengths  z0h_z0m_c  z0h_z0m_rf
l_moruses_storage    = F  Canopy heat capacity        ch_c       ch_rf
                          Fractional canopy coverage  vf_c       vf_rf

albsnf_rf and emis_rf do not require setting here as they are not parameterised
by MORUSES and are therefore entered with the previous parameter table.


