Empirical relationships (l_urban_empirical)
------------------------------------------
This enables empirical relationships between urban fraction and urban geometry
giving wrr "w/r ratio", hwr "h/w ratio" & hgt where:
      w = width of the canyon
      r = width of the canyon + roof
hgt = h = height of buildings

If this option is not enabled then the user must prescribe their own values and
provide ancillary data instead.

URBAN-2T requires wrr (= fraction of urban tile that is canyon)
MORUSES  requires wrr, hwr & hgt

These empirical relationships were derived from correlating CEH urban fraction
and LUCID urban geometry data for London. Obtained from collaboration with the
University of Reading. See:
    Bohnenstengel, S.I., Evans, S., Clark, P., Belcher, S.E. (2010);
    Simulations of the London urban heat island, Q.J.R.Meteorol. Soc., to
    be submitted.
for more information

WARNINGS:

* For MORUSES if the empirical relationships are used then so must the
  MacDonald (1998) formulation for roughness length for momentum and
  displacement height

* These relationships are resolution dependent as they are based on urban
  fraction. They are therefore only valid for high resolution i.e. UKV.



Anthropogenic heat source (l_anthrop_heat_src)
---------------------------------------------
Adds a seasonal dependent amount to the surface heat fluxes (Wm-2) in urban
tiles. Values are derived for Northern Hemisphere mid latitude cities, so its
scope is limited to these regions.

* URBAN-2T / MORUSES
The anthropogenic heat flux (anthrop_heat) is spread between the urban_canyon
and urban_roof tiles depending on a distribution scale factor
(anthrop_heat_scale) where:

                 H_roof                 = anthrop_heat_scale * H_canyon

H_canyon * wrr + H_roof * ( 1.0 - wrr ) = anthrop_heat

anthrop_heat_scale has a value 0.0 - 1.0 where the extremes correspond to:

0.0 = all released within the canyon
1.0 = evenly spread between canyon and roof

There is a check in place to ensure that the anthropogenic heat flux is
conserved. The default is 1.0 to be consistent with the original urban scheme.



Note on emissivity
------------------

Currently as most of the JULES parameters are not able to be changed through
the UMUI, the user must be careful when changing the emissivity. If the
emissivity chosen in atmos_Science_Section_LSurf is changed from 0.97 i.e.

L_EMIS_LAND_GEN  = .TRUE.
EMIS_LAND_GEN   !=  0.97

in &NLSTCATM, then this does not carry through to the JULES land surface
model; JULES has 0.97 as default. To make JULES consistent a hand edit
is required to modify &JULES_NVEGPARM and &JULES_PFTPARM. If URBAN-2T or
non default MORUSES is chosen then &URBAN2T_PARAM should also be edited.

